title.narrative: ACCESS TO QUALITY COMMUNITY AND INSTITUTIONAL HEALT SERVICES

description.narrative: By 2020, health workers (institutional and community) are capable of providing quality prevention and treatment services in the vulnerable regions, including in emergency situations, which contributes to Immunization, Maternal And Newborn Health, Maternal And Newborn Health (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Children and women in vulnerable regions have access to and use a package of quality promotional, preventive and curative health interventions, including in emergency situations.

description.narrative: 190/192 multitask community health workers were technically equipped to maintain service provision in COVID-19 context and in implementation of barrier measures. Through them, women and children are still receiving essential community-based health services in the Far-North and North regions. The training received by 118 health professionals and 122 CHW permitted 72 COVID-19 women have had safe delivery and others are enjoying an inch free pregnancy. Last but not the least, 180 preterm and low birth weight infants received kangaroo mother care in the 5 UNICEF-supported health districts in the East region. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:30/06/2020
